Your code executes top-to-bottom automatically. But what if you only want certain code to run when a user is logged in? You use **Conditionals**.

**`if` statement**
The IF statement runs code *only* if its condition magically evaluates to `true` (or a loosely "truthy" value like a populated string).
```javascript
let money = 10;
if (money > 5) {
    console.log("You can afford this!");
}
```

**`else if` and `else`**
You can chain alternative conditions securely using `else if`. If every single condition violently fails, the `else` block catches it.
```javascript
if (score == 100) {
    alert("Perfect!");
} else if (score > 50) {
    alert("Pass");
} else {
    alert("Fail");
}
```

**Ternary Operator (The One-Line IF)**
If you have a brutally simple `if/else` that just rigidly assigns a variable, you can drastically compress it using the Ternary Operator `? :`.
`let status = (age >= 18) ? "Adult" : "Child";`
(If age >= 18 is true, it assigns Adult. If false, it assigns Child).

**`switch` statement**
When you have an insane chain of 10 `else if` statements aggressively checking the *same exact variable* against different exact values, a `switch` is much cleaner!
```javascript
switch (mode) {
    case "dark": setDarkMode(); break;
    case "light": setLightMode(); break;
    default: setSystemMode();
}
```
The `break` keyword is absolutely critical to stop it from spilling into the next cases!

**Error Handling Control Flow (`try/catch/finally`)**
When your JavaScript hits a fatal error (like a failing network request), the entire script violently crashes, abruptly destroying the webpage.

To prevent this, you intelligently wrap dangerous operations in a `try` block. If the engine detects an explosion, it instantly pauses the script and reroutes the panic directly into the `catch` block—preventing the crash entirely!
```javascript
try {
   riskyFunction(); // If this crashes...
} catch (err) {
   console.log("Caught the fire!", err.message); // This runs instead of dying
} finally {
   console.log("I always run no matter what");
}
```
You can even fiercely trigger your own deliberate crashes structurally using `throw new Error("Bad Input");`.
